# GitHub Releases on App Version Bumps

Whenever a new app version is committed and pushed, **always** create a GitHub Release immediately after pushing — do not wait for the user to ask.

## Steps (in order)

1. Commit and push the code changes as normal.
2. Create a git tag matching the version (e.g. `android-v1.2.4`) pointing at the new commit.
3. Push the tag: `git push origin <tag>`.
4. Create the GitHub release with `gh release create`, attaching the APK from `android/dist/`:

```bash
gh release create android-v<X.Y.Z> \
  "android/dist/openRS_v<X.Y.Z>.apk#openRS_v<X.Y.Z>.apk" \
  --title "openRS_ v<X.Y.Z> — <short description>" \
  --latest \
  --notes "<release notes>"
```

## Rules

- Mark the newest release as `--latest`.
- Release notes must summarise **what changed and why** (not just "bug fixes").
- APK must be the signed release build from `android/dist/`, not a debug build.
- If multiple versions are committed in one session, create a release for each one.
